FAA: Air passengers can now use aircraft gadgets (but not calling with their mobile phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies and listening to music – but not speaking on their mobile phone – under the new highly expected guidelines published by the Federal Aviation Administration Thursday.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be put in place will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated crew member training manuals and the rules on aircraft storage to be in conformity.
The FAA said it had already received plans from certain airlines to expand the use of electronic aircraft on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are one of the companies that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the plan, we could approve widespread use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to re-light them before the plane reached an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives its green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the plane is descended before the landing and do not turn them back until the plane has launched.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interferences will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during departures, landing and soil rolling, the FAA said.
Most new line aircraft and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, chairman of the Association of Professional Flight Attendees, said he was happy with these changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with carriers for this – it will be profitable to everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
We are honestly tired of feeling like “hall supervisors” when it comes to this issue.
But it will always be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and SMS, or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in aircraft mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble style online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was expelled with noise from an American Airlines aircraft after refusing to turn off his aircraft while the aircraft was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always need to be arranged because they could hurt someone if they were flying through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be prohibited.
The regulatory power regarding mobile phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not to the FAA.
FAA can lift the prohibition on certain electronic devices during landing and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said mobile phones were always considered to be at risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could eventually create interferences with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone antennas if they are used on board,” Rosenker said.
An Industrial Advisory Committee established by the FAA to review the problem last month recommended that the government authorize wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased over the past few years to simplify restrictions on their use.
Detractors such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo. argue that there is no valid safety reason for these prohibitions.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to apply because the use of devices has become omnipresent.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to shut off their devices, or do so deliberately.
FAA began to limit the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports on the presence of interferences with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of then.
New line planes are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of planes, but they are also designed to resist electronic interferences and approved by FAA.
Airlines allow their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Modified aircraft to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also better resisting interferences.
The vast majority of line aircraft should enable wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit lower power radio transmissions than previous generations of devices.
Electronic book readers, for example, only issue minimum transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is one of those who pressure to remove the restrictions regarding the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company’s leaders loaded a Kindle e-book reader line plane and flyed it to see if there were any problems, but there was none.
This inspired members of the FAA Advisory Committee of mitigated feelings regarding whether or not the use of devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he thought interference from the aircraft was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there are only anecdotic reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with plane systems, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that FAA authorize pilots to request passengers to shut off their aircraft during instrument landing under conditions of low visibility.
A group of the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them to arrangements full of meaning for travelers equipped with technology.
“We are happy that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with security,” said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
