We have discovered that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that modernize and grow while EU states stagn.
They want to see the government give priority to new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil rather than engaging in the long and hard process of reforming European institutional arcans.
When asked for their opinions on specific political aspects – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – the majority of business leaders think that control of these key skills should return to Westminster’s hands.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, companies saying that the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate from the benefits to be part of the European trade area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European companies, even agree.
Finally, and even more, our survey with business leaders revealed that a majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives in favour of a change in the treaty and the development of a trade-based relationship with the EU and not politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and businesses of all sizes, shows that the world of the company insists on a “significant change” that returns power to the UK.
The challenges are high – achieving changing the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would allow 16% of the votes to maintain the country in the EU during a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not doubt once: this investigation shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain’s membership to the EU.
It also shows that companies hope that renegotiation will constitute a significant change in the current balance of power in favour of a return to the UK.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to be better represent the interests of British companies, since the euro area is committed to a narrow economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be employment and growth in Britain and, as the conclusions of our survey show, this means for businesses re-focusing on trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels regulatory approach.
