How Biometrics Invade Our Lives
Does your passwords end up in order to access your smartphone or pay your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict us a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Chief Executive Officer of Morpho, even believes that “the century will be biometric.”
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for IT and Freedoms has authorized 774 systems for recognition of footprints, the shape of the hand or the veinous network of hand in companies, administrations, cantines...
"Everybody will soon be identified, anywhere and anytime," says Justin Brookman, Consumer Privacy Officer of the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, among others, and pessimism, among others?
The biometry will rely on new techniques that will enable new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, the most used biometric data in France are the fingerprints, the hand contour and the veinous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
“For example, some people working on concrete have very damaged fingers and their imprints are illegible,” says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of the Identity Domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the veinous network and the contour of the hand implies a voluntary and accurate gesture of people.
It is both a safety - one cannot capture this data at their uncertainty - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been conducted for about 20 years on other approaches, such as face recognition or iris (the colorful part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the calculation capacity of computers necessary for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border stations using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of Intel Labs Security Research.
Unique and infalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But the analysis of DNA is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples on the place of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (acknowledge one person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is the one he claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issue of identity papers: the biometric elements (fingerprints, photographs, iris) must be confronted with the information that the State has on all citizens already identified.
This makes sure that someone does not attempt to usurp the identity of someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
“We recover the images of surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities circulating freely on the Internet,” explains Dany Nassif, who is responsible for NEC France’s business development for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: taking a picture that makes the tail in a store, follow its progression through facial recognition and calculating the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (boundary, protected places, cantines...) or logical access (a computer opening).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"One biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend that points for another," says Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those carried out from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to remove money from some distributors by introducing his card and putting his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the strike of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and in Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and big distribution signs: at the time of paying in store with its credit card, the customer does not stick his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers might soon arrive with French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometric attractive in the eyes of the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer remains in the box thirty seconds less, it’s appreciable,” said the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer customized services: within a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second basis: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which blocks if we try to move it,” Philippe Robin, de Thales, says.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to be concerned.
“The progress in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me afraid of the worst: a widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick from the Office of Privacy Protection in Canada.
