Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s perspective), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to see what it was in other species.
He added that, like in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordinated tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching films where other dogs were included.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will certainly not take a long time before we understand why their tail goes sometimes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained, “We have presented to dogs films where other dogs were included – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factor – and we have been able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression moving the tail to the right (from the view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail diverting primarily to the left (once again from the tail moving dog's perspective), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs would deliberately communicate with each other thanks to these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not be concerned.
He added: “If you meet other dogs repeatedly and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on this experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, invited professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the dog species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a joyful dog.
In another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, “Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when his tail moved to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study.”
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that dogs who participated in different studies did not entirely consider film animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will certainly not take a long time before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
