A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of bump dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, a scientific mission at the Observatory for the Conservation and the Study of Animals and Miliar Marines (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of dolphin surprise you?
It's a good news, but I don't surprise it particularly.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on the basis of morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
It is not possible that such progress in genetics and molecular biology would challenge the classification or belonging of a species to a genre, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged because of the progress in genetics.
Similarly, two very close species have been distinguished morphologically thanks to genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific bump dolphins and the Atlantic bump whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as the Wildlife Conservation Society said?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we might have dealt with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or in extinction based on the number of existing individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility it has to recover from neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new species discovered is coming out, its stock became automatically weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
In contrast, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can result in the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, rather than knowing what lives in the Marianne's graves, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money in searching for life on other planets than in marine research and it’s time to change.
