You can leave the house at 5 o'clock, run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father's death in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 physician for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty threshold, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s health expenditure are made in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” said Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot benefit from life.
After seeing his father and as much of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed more than 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital of Yaoundé.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas during weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they sit in vans after setting medical equipment on the roof and crossing tough grounds to go to the villages that most need help.
Luck doesn’t always follow them.
They have always had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or boiled tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sing and dance and offers them the best accommodation available.
