The next morning, the team starts receiving hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people every visit,” Bwelle said.
Sometimes they live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can receive beads, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate – document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical actions under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, town hall or house; after the intervention, the patient gets up and goes to the awakening room to leave his place to the next person.
Through the lighting of the electronics group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s an exciting pace, but village musicians generally help the team remain motivated.
“They are hitting drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue to work,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work she has done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, practiced 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year, and he knows that their presence can make all the difference for those to whom they come to help.
A man explained that the free operation he had undergone to cure hernia would allow him to work again.
“This will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to making this traveling hospital live and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
This is the second job, he explains, which finances his association at 60%; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he sleeps,” said Katie O’Malley, a medical student in the second year of Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer in the group of Dr. Bwelle.
He is always in the hospital or trying to find money for his association to be able to conduct these campaigns.
For medical students and nurse students such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, it is an opportunity to learn on the field that they don't have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help sponge the blood or bring the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” Miss O’Malley said.
It’s not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you’re a medical student in the second year.
Volunteers generally pay their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transport and teaching are supported by Dr. Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” Katie O’Malley said.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not near to turn off.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happy by holding the promise he has made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle added.
And I think of my father.
I hope he'll see what I'm doing.
To make people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons that force me to do this.
